## Quick Start

```bash
# 1. Clone and enter the project
git clone https://github.com/YOUR_USERNAME/fedtb_nigeria.git
cd fedtb_nigeria

# 2. Create the conda environment
conda env create -f environment.yml
conda activate fedtb_nigeria

# 3. Download datasets (interactive, asks before large downloads)
python scripts/download_data.py

# 4. Run tests on mock data
pytest tests/ -v

# 5. Run the full pipeline (takes several hours with GPU)
python scripts/run_all.py

# 6. Or open notebooks in order
jupyter lab notebooks/
```

---

## Hardware Requirements

| Mode | Hardware | Estimated Time |
|---|---|---|
| Mock data only (tests) | CPU only | ~5 minutes |
| Single-site centralised | GPU (4GB+) | ~2 hours |
| Full FL simulation (3 sites) | GPU (8GB+) | ~6–12 hours |
| Full FL + DP (50 rounds) | GPU (8GB+) | ~12–24 hours |

*All notebooks include `USE_MOCK_DATA = True` flags to run quickly on CPU.*

---

## Reproducibility

- All random seeds are fixed (see `configs/config.yaml`)
- All preprocessing is fit on training data only (no leakage)
- All train/val/test splits are stratified and site-aware
- All reported metrics include 95% bootstrap confidence intervals

---

## Ethical Considerations

- No real patient data are included in this repository
- Datasets used are publicly released for research purposes
- Differential privacy budgets are reported transparently
- Fairness analysis across simulated hospital sites is included
- Limitations of the site-simulation approach are explicitly discussed
- See `paper_or_report/limitations.md` for full discussion

